## ----hetero, fig.cap = "Split-conformal prediction intervals on a one-dimensional heteroscedastic problem at target coverage 0.90. Grey points show 400 training observations drawn from a sine signal with heteroscedastic Gaussian noise. Shaded bands are 200 test-point intervals from \\texttt{conformal\\_split()} with \\texttt{score\\_type = \"absolute\"} (left, empirical coverage 0.890, mean width 5.45) and \\texttt{score\\_type = \"normalized\"} (right, empirical coverage 0.905, mean width 5.34). The normalised scoring produces narrower intervals where noise is low without losing coverage.", fig.alt = "A two-panel scatter plot of 400 training points under a sinusoidal signal with noise that grows with the input. The left panel shows absolute-residual conformal intervals as a constant-width band around the fitted curve. The right panel shows normalised-residual intervals that narrow near the left edge where noise is low and widen toward the right where noise is higher. Both panels report empirical coverage near 0.90 and similar mean interval widths."----
